00:04:19.279 --> 00:04:23.279
Well, to get us started here, I get to ask you a few questions while we wait for them

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:29.279
to come in from everybody. But I was curious, what actually got you into the world of data

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:31.279
initially?

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:39.279
So I had a really, I would say probably ordinary experience in college. I was studying statistics

00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:43.279
and political science. And at that time, political science had become primarily a quantitative

00:04:43.279 --> 00:04:50.279
field focused on understanding the relationships between voting behaviors, election results.

00:04:50.279 --> 00:04:56.279
And a lot of that mapped to the types of inferential statistics and causational models that we

00:04:56.279 --> 00:05:02.279
have today. I think the best example is when President Obama was running, that was really

00:05:02.279 --> 00:05:08.279
the first time that you saw a lot more investment in digital marketing, essentially, as a way

00:05:08.279 --> 00:05:11.279
of influencing voting behavior.

00:05:11.279 --> 00:05:16.279
And so when I started, I was using the tools that universities use, which are essentially

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:24.279
paid statistical tools like SPSS. Once I left that academic environment and was going into

00:05:24.279 --> 00:05:29.279
my career, I realized I'm not going to have access to SPSS. IBM had purchased that product

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:35.279
by that time, and it was on the order of $4,000 or $5,000 for a license. And so I discovered

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:42.279
R. And R and RStudio just gave me essentially a key to open up my career, a key to a bigger

00:05:42.279 --> 00:05:46.279
world, and a way of helping to accomplish the goals I was trying to accomplish in my

00:05:46.279 --> 00:05:50.279
own career while having a community to support me.

00:05:51.279 --> 00:05:57.279
And so that's also led to myself and a colleague starting up a data consulting business of our

00:05:57.279 --> 00:06:03.279
own called Paradigm Data Group. And a lot of what we do is spend time giving support

00:06:03.279 --> 00:06:08.279
to communities that don't have a lot of attention. So, for example, in my own local community,

00:06:08.279 --> 00:06:15.279
we built the Shiny app for our university, and that Shiny app delivers essentially inferential

00:06:15.279 --> 00:06:20.279
data about how we are delivering food to the needy in our community and where we can do

00:06:20.279 --> 00:06:26.279
better and how many people we're serving and our progress over time. And last year, we

00:06:26.279 --> 00:06:34.279
helped to train the L.A. County Public Health Department in RStudio and the languages that

00:06:34.279 --> 00:06:38.279
we use in addition to that as well as the packages. And so there's a lot of opportunity,

00:06:38.279 --> 00:06:43.279
I think, and a lot of growth opportunity for organizations that want to get into open source.

00:06:43.279 --> 00:06:48.279
And there are loads of people that are willing to help, and I think that's one of the things

00:06:48.279 --> 00:06:51.279
that has been such a value for me over time.

00:06:54.279 --> 00:06:59.279
So if somebody is here, like, listening on the Hangout, and is that a company that doesn't

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:04.279
have a marketing analytics team, but they're interested in building out their first use

00:07:04.279 --> 00:07:07.279
case for it, what would you recommend when getting started?

00:07:08.279 --> 00:07:15.279
I would recommend, I think, if I was to go into any technology or non-technology company

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:21.279
and there was not a team or there was a beginning team, the first thing I would do is have a

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:26.279
meeting with every executive or the most senior leaders I could at that organization and ask

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:33.279
them the questions they're trying to answer. I think that one of the ways that you can

00:07:33.279 --> 00:07:38.279
be derailed or be prevented from being successful in any data role, especially in a marketing

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:44.279
analytics role, is to not capture those core questions. So the first thing I would do is

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:48.279
go in and ask, you know, what are the core questions you're trying to answer? I would

00:07:48.279 --> 00:07:53.279
then understand what the infrastructure we have available is. Are we capturing data that's

00:07:53.279 --> 00:07:58.279
able to measure the things we need, the metrics we need in order to answer those questions?

00:07:58.279 --> 00:08:03.279
If not, what are the lightest weight tools that we can spin up? And then I would start

00:08:03.279 --> 00:08:09.279
answering the lowest hanging fruit first. So I think a lot of it is about being able to

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:16.279
build yourself a reproducible analytical framework and build the communication first. In my

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:22.279
experience, building trust is the quickest way to be successful. And that really means

00:08:22.279 --> 00:08:29.279
doing good work, but it also means communicating your work and being someone that is engaging,

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:35.280
being someone who's available. And so I would really start out with those first three steps.

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.280
What are the questions we're trying to answer? How are we going to be able to answer them

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:44.280
given the technology and infrastructure we have in our data? And then what is the lightest

00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:49.280
question I can answer first that gets me started building trust?

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:55.280
Thank you. I'm seeing a lot of love for marketing analytics in the chat and people who are

00:08:55.280 --> 00:09:02.280
working in marketing analytics. I see, Sol, you had asked a question a little bit earlier.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:04.280
Do you want to jump in?

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:10.280
Yeah, I can. Can you guys hear me? Sorry.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:13.280
I can, but you're, okay, I was like you were invisible for a second.

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:18.280
Yeah, thanks for hopping on, Peter. Yeah, my question was a little bit related to your

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:24.280
SPSS experience and I guess now with R. Do you have experience with training people who

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:30.280
aren't familiar with R on R and would love to hear about how some of that's gone, some

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:36.280
learning, some takeaways? Because I think a lot of teams have tools like SPSS or other

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:43.280
things, and then the benefits of R are pretty obvious to me. And so sometimes I try to understand

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:45.280
how to bridge that gap. Thank you.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:52.280
Yeah, absolutely. So that is part of what I do when I'm not at work is Paradigm Data

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:58.280
Group trains, like I said, the example I was giving is training folks at the LA County

00:09:58.280 --> 00:10:03.280
Public Health Department. And the example I think with them is very good because it's

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:09.280
a timeline, right? The LA County Public Health Department is the largest of its kind and

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:16.280
probably in the world, at least in America. And as COVID started ramping up during the

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:22.280
pandemic in 2020, there started to be a greater and greater need for reproducibility. Analysis

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:28.280
that could be put into analytical frameworks that were built in code and where the results

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:36.280
of those could be shared across domains and across other tools. And that is an example

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:44.280
I think of exactly what you're suggesting, Sol, is how can we do this in code? And you're

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:50.280
right, when you have a really large org and they're not sensitive to costs, you might

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:56.280
have something like SPSS. I would say that that's probably more marginal these days rather

00:10:57.280 --> 00:11:04.280
than the greatest density of data users. But in that case, it really starts from doing

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:08.280
what kind of what I suggested before, which is let's find out what your team wants to

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:13.280
answer. Let's find out a problem that we can solve together. And then let's use the parts

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:18.280
of the language. And intentionally, I always start with a tidy verse because it's like

00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:24.280
how we construct sentences, right? It's a verb, subjects, and objects. And that can

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:29.280
get you off to a very fast start. And I think it also has the benefit of building trust,

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:36.280
right? You're delivering something to a stakeholder that answers a question. And it gets you started

00:11:36.280 --> 00:11:41.280
in being able to work one-on-one with someone who maybe has more experience and is more

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:48.280
comfortable in the language. Gotcha. Or do you have any funny, I guess, snags along the

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:55.280
way? I imagine a lot of teams also use SQL, SQL Server. What's your experience in getting

00:11:55.280 --> 00:12:01.280
teams to connect to these databases? I've had some pushback on IT, security, sensitivity

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:07.280
of data, access. But I try to evangelize R, but those seem to be pretty big obstacles

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:13.280
for me. I think the best way to handle... So I've been writing SQL, I guess, for maybe

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:18.280
15 years. I haven't ever... And that's going to be an essential skill in any technology

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:22.280
company, right? Because every database is cloud database these days. So you're accessing

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:29.280
it through something like Snowflake or Databricks. And in that case, you're going to be able

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:37.280
to connect through either the IDE on your desktop or through the platform tools that

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:43.280
Posit offers. So Posit offers tools where if you would like to, you could simply write

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:51.280
SQL inside of a browser window, right? That browser window is essentially is when we're

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:57.280
connected to an instance in the cloud. And then you're pulling down data through the

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:06.280
connection that you build inside of the IDE. It's relatively easy. And it's an example

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:12.280
of essentially usually two lines of code. There's a passkey and there's a library that

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:20.280
allows you to connect to those databases. I would suggest that if it's a security question,

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:25.280
that you really look at the resources available through Posit. This is something that is very,

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:30.280
very common, but I can tell you it's easily overcome. When I worked at Lyft, for example,

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:38.280
we were advocating to use Posit's platform tools and it was not a challenge. I think you just

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:45.280
have to be able to demonstrate the security and what's under the hood of Posit. If the

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:51.280
company like Lyft is comfortable with their data being passed through this connection,

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:56.280
I can't imagine anybody else wouldn't be happy.

00:13:56.280 --> 00:13:58.280
No, super helpful. Thank you so much.

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:00.280
Sure.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:05.280
Thank you. I see Arthi asked a question in the chat. I'll read it out. But it's being a

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:11.280
marketing analyst, I know how fast paced every day is. How do you help your team prioritize

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:17.280
requests and have you faced situations where you recommend strategy changes, but the business

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:19.280
doesn't want to implement them?

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:27.280
Absolutely. Let's start with how do you manage the day to day? So the way that I work primarily

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:33.280
is through prioritizing our workflows, meaning what we're, which projects we're going to

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:41.280
execute on and resource to based on size and sensitivity. So for example, I have a very

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:47.280
simple framework of where I measure the size of a project. What is its contribution to

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:53.280
the organization? How are we defining that contribution? And it is a sort of arithmetic way of

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:59.280
doing it. It's quantitative, but it also needs to ladder up to one of the strategic goals of

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:07.280
the organization. So choose an example. At Toast, for example, you know, one of the strategic

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:14.280
goals of Toast, like all SaaS companies, is acquiring new customers. So if we have a project

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:19.280
that is focused on that, and there will be many projects focused on new customer acquisition,

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:24.280
how do we compare those different projects to each other? Meaning what is the size potential

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:29.280
of the contribution of each one of those projects? Is this going to get us, you know, 100 new

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:35.280
customers, 1,000? So I would first focus on prioritizing based upon the influence, the effect,

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:40.280
the impact of the project itself. And make sure that you're working with your stakeholders.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:45.280
If you're reporting into a director or a manager or something, make sure that you, you know,

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:50.280
spend time and take the opportunity with that manager to sit down and say, hey, you know, I'd like

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:56.280
to be able to more effectively manage my work. Maybe I feel overloaded. I don't have time to do

00:15:56.280 --> 00:16:01.280
the quality of work that I would like to. And here's a framework in which I'm thinking about using

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:07.280
with my partners to size projects. And then internally as a data team, you can discuss those

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:15.280
and prioritize them yourself. When it comes to changing strategy, that typically comes from

00:16:15.280 --> 00:16:20.280
an analysis, meaning some data product, some data science product you've created.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:29.280
I can give you an example. Oftentimes in marketing, what we really care about is are we getting

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:34.280
close to our goal or plan for the organization? Meaning like if we say we're going to deliver

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:39.280
a thousand customers this month, are we delivering, are we pacing to that?

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:45.280
If you're not pacing to that, which will occur from time to time, you need to understand why.

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:53.280
And so you might create an analysis that surfaces that maybe a channel is underperforming.

00:16:53.280 --> 00:16:59.280
Maybe something has changed in your acquisition funnel. And you need to understand how this change

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:08.280
is contributing, say, negatively to your goal. If that's the case, then you need to be able to first

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:15.280
identify the problem, define it, to be able to express how it is related to the same thing,

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:24.280
to one of the strategic goals of the organization, and communicate that to your team.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:28.280
And once you communicate that to your team, make recommendations on how you think you could attack

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:34.280
answering this question. What are the types of analytical tools you could use to understand

00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:39.280
what the problem is? And then if you can define that problem, if you can define the influences

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:49.280
of that problem, sort of the root cause of that problem, then you can make recommendations

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:57.280
to strategic changes. Marketing has a bit of a challenge compared to most product analytic roles,

00:17:57.280 --> 00:18:03.280
where the marketing funnels themselves can change on a regular basis depending upon tactics

00:18:03.280 --> 00:18:11.280
that change. And so oftentimes you'll see volatility or variations that are out of the norm,

00:18:11.280 --> 00:18:15.280
and you need to be able to work with your marketing partners to understand how they may be contributing

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:23.280
to those changes, and be able to tell that story back to the business.

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:30.280
Okay, maybe a quick, fun question, but what did you want to be when you were a little kid?

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:37.280
It's funny, when I was a kid, my parents spent a lot of time traveling with us. I have a twin brother,

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:42.280
and we spent a lot of time traveling, and my dad was a geologist, so we spent a lot of time

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:49.280
in national parks. And I think when I was a kid, there was nothing better than being outside.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:57.280
And I think even now, I think about, like, how could I do my job with more travel involved?

00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:04.280
But I didn't really have a specific career path or anything in mind. I was mostly just very curious,

00:19:04.280 --> 00:19:08.280
and I knew that I was interested in kind of understanding how people work.

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:15.280
And I think that's why political science was so interesting to me. It was sort of getting to how people make choices.

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:21.280
And a lot of what I do today is trying to understand how people are choosing one thing rather than another.

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:26.280
What are those different types of signals that people's behavior gives that we can use

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:31.280
to better understand what might happen in the future?

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:37.280
Definitely. I love that. J.U., I see you had a question in the chat on decision frameworks.

