probabilistic attribution of these customers? Or what are we doing? And what is the new shift?

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:52.280
I mean, there's a lot of research that has been going on in the customer centricity framework.

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:57.280
I mean, I'm hearing that a lot of people are moving away from that shift now.

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:05.280
So what have you been doing in industry and what type of decisions do stakeholders make from that specific product set?

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:10.280
I know it's a specific use case. You may not have the answers, but feel free to deviate it from it.

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:13.280
Let's talk about that. So you mentioned the term ROI, right?

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:15.280
Yes. Yes.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:19.280
So that's a that's going to be a common point of talk.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:22.280
I would say a point of conversation generally with any finance partner.

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:30.280
So one of all marketing partners, no matter where you are, is going to be a finance team because that's who holds the budget for marketing.

00:21:30.280 --> 00:21:36.280
And the job of finance, like the job of, you know, any good finance teams to be skeptical.

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:44.280
You know, if a marketer says, like, I need a thousand dollars to acquire a customer, they're going to say, why do you need a thousand dollars?

00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:50.280
And you should have observational data, right? You should take an empirical approach to this.

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:55.280
What is the empirical evidence that suggests you need a thousand dollars to acquire a customer?

00:21:55.280 --> 00:22:01.280
So it does start with every like every other analytical exercise.

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:12.280
It does start with EDA. It starts with exploratory analysis where you're providing, you know, descriptive statistics on the performance of your marketing.

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:26.280
Let me let me use an example. So, for example, if we want to evaluate the return on investment, how much you're returning in revenue compared to what you're spending.

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:31.280
That can happen in both a probabilistic way.

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:34.280
So, for example, like it can happen in an incrementality study.

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:45.280
Or it can happen in a naive way, which is, for example, you spend a thousand dollars on a Facebook ad and you get eleven hundred dollars back.

00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:52.280
And so your return is essentially a hundred dollars, the 10 percent marginal return on your spending.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:23:03.280
So I think that depending upon where you are with the finance team, depending on what your organization is like, there will be more skeptical or less skeptical.

00:23:03.280 --> 00:23:11.280
I think one of the one of the ways marketers often work is they create exactly that example I gave.

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:22.280
So create a CPA, a cost per acquisition number. It's based upon a set of assumptions and that cost per acquisition number is largely arbitrary.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:30.280
It's something that they usually think that they can achieve, but it's not based upon efficiency, meaning how low could it possibly be?

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:39.280
And that's when you start having to have more causal frameworks, meaning incrementality studies.

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:48.280
And those come in a variety of flavors, whether it's a randomized controlled experiment, whether it's a geomapping, geomatching experiment.

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:57.280
But at the end of all those experiments, there should be some metric that you can validate internally on your own data.

00:23:58.280 --> 00:24:22.280
I think that the one of the challenges for all marketing teams is being able to make those causal statements, meaning that if we spend another hundred thousand dollars, a million dollars, ten million dollars, we will know that this marginal difference is incremental, meaning it would not we would not get this revenue if we didn't spend this money.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:43.280
Those are the most challenging questions to answer, and I think that is where oftentimes marketing teams and finance teams can get disconnected, is that there's a lot of value for the marketers or the marketing analytics folks should be spending time communicating these concepts.

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:54.280
Evangelize for measurement, but spend a lot of time on communicating the concepts of causality and how you're going to define success.

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:01.280
Thank you.

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:09.280
I think this might be Sunday. You said you have a question that's similar to the current one, so I'm going to jump to yours if you want to go next.

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:14.280
Thanks, Rachel. Yeah, Sunday I work with Premier Incorporated Senior Research Analyst.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:23.280
I'm just interested in knowing, do recommender algorithms play any role in your work?

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:30.280
I know very often people think of them, those in like context of like, you know, shopping sales and that kind of thing.

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:45.280
But, you know, for your work as a marketer, you know, analysts in that space, do this, how much do this play a role in, you know, your work or any other algorithms probably that you use?

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:53.280
When you say algorithms, do you mean algorithms that we use to measure marketing performance or the algorithms of the platforms that are delivering the ads?

00:25:53.280 --> 00:26:04.280
It's neither this or that, you know, when I think about, you know, whatever recommender systems, especially I'm interested in those, do they play any role at all, at any level?

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:22.280
Yes, absolutely. So I'll give you an example. At Nextdoor, you know, one of the things that we're always trying to accomplish is increasing engagement on the platform, meaning getting people to log in, to connect with each other, to communicate with each other.

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:38.280
So delivering value to the members of the platform. And in our case, one of the objectives we had was creating more connections between users. So, I mean, we want to see people connecting with each other so that they can communicate.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:57.280
And in that case, we developed our own algorithm, which essentially was a distance measure, to think of like a cosine distance or something like that. We developed an algorithm based upon a distance measurement and then features about users themselves in order to recommend who they should connect to.

00:26:58.280 --> 00:27:17.280
And that, so that plays a very critical role in also how we deliver ads, right? We want to make sure that the ads themselves are relevant to the person receiving them. And we know certain things about users, we have features about them, and we can measure similarity to the success of an ad with somebody like that.

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:31.280
So, for example, if an ad is successful with me, and there's someone who has a very similar profile to me based upon some metric that we can create from an algorithm, like a distance metric, we might serve that other person the same ad.

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:55.280
We also did that, something similar on our advertising platform. So, Nextdoor advertises small businesses. And what we want to see is that people are clicking on those ads and engaging with the businesses on Nextdoor. And so we would explore different models, different algorithms in order to rank those ads.

00:27:56.280 --> 00:28:19.280
And it could be even something as simple as an algorithm that ranks the density of ads, meaning like how many ads do you see while you're scrolling? And ads have positions inside of platforms like Facebook and Instagram and Nextdoor, and you have to be selective about how do you, how dense do you want those placements to be?

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:34.280
So you're right, it matters. Those algorithms are important for re-recommending connections or relationships, but those relationships could be a number of things. It could be a relationship from you to a company or you to another user.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:47.280
Thanks. Just a real quick one is, do you, how do you then measure, you know, your improvements afterwards?

00:28:47.280 --> 00:29:01.280
Right, right. Great question. So you need to have a metric. All experiments really require two things from the outset, at least, which is you need a metric that's sensitive enough to change during the observational period.

00:29:02.280 --> 00:29:29.280
So you need to know, you know, how sensitive is this metric? Then you also need a metric that you know represents getting closer to your goal. So, for example, if we wanted to understand if we were increasing engagement on the platform, and we say engagement is defined as the percentage of days in the month that you're on Nextdoor, we can't wait a month to run that experiment.

00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:47.280
Right? So we need some metric that correlates with that. And we know one of the things that correlates with that is your connections, the number of connections you have. And so we chose connections as our experiment metric, meaning the objective function of that experiment.

00:29:48.280 --> 00:30:04.280
And then we would be able to identify, you know, if we ran this experiment on, you know, X number of users, we would expect hypothetically based on effect size, say 10% increase or 15% marginal increase, this many new connections.

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:25.280
And we'd be able to then have a power analysis to determine, you know, a sensitivity analysis to determine if that was going to be sufficient to be confident on that result. So it's about making sure that you're selecting the right thing to measure, which can sink an experiment, right? Because if you say, oh, we need six months to run this, you know, you're probably going to get some pushback.

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:42.280
And then you're going to have to have a metric that ensures it's correlated with something up funnel from the final objective that you're interested in. And in marketing, similar to those ad placements in marketing, what we're interested in oftentimes is revenue.

00:30:42.280 --> 00:31:07.280
But, you know, a precursor to revenue is people clicking on ads. Are we getting more clicks per session, for example, per user on ads? And so you have to think of it sort of as a sequel, I think all things as a sequence. And what you want to do is work upstream in that sequence, where you can define the relationship from those down to those down funnel events.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:20.280
Thank you. So, I guess, thinking about the data science hangout space, like, how would you recommend they go about measuring like positive impact of the space?

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:23.280
Of the hangout itself?

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:24.280
Yeah.

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:25.280
Yeah, absolutely.

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:32.280
I'm just saying this, I'm just thinking about that. It's hard to measure like the great vibes in the community and everybody hanging out here.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:32:01.280
I would first think about, like, what is the objective of this, right? There are many, right? But many of the objectives are part of the product itself. Like, Posit wants to create a community for all of us to support each other. That means reaching out to each other, too, right? Like, when you log into the open forums, they're going to be people that are not just going to give you, you know, sort of what I'm doing is like a narrative of a framework or something.

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:20.280
But really give you help to create a solution. And so I think that part of the value of this hangout is definitely the level of engagement, right? And I would think of engagement as something that you can measure over time. How many people are joining this hangout?

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:39.280
And this is the way we would measure this on any social platform, right? How many people are commenting? How many people are reacting to comments? What is the average number of reactions per comment? What is the density of those comments? Meaning, what is the percentage of people in the hangout that deliver a comment?

00:32:40.280 --> 00:32:54.280
How is, like, what is the curve line sort of look like of the number of attendees over time? Like, is it growing in that that line is very steep or is it starting to flatten and it's a little bit sort of reaching its apex?

00:32:54.280 --> 00:33:14.280
I would also start thinking about, can you extract learnings from the actual content itself, right? Like, what are the subjects? If we were to plot the distribution of attendees against, and we were to look at that over time, and we, and that's a scatterplot, right? Like, what is that over time?

00:33:14.280 --> 00:33:30.280
If we labeled those points in the scatterplot, what is the topic of that hangout, right? So then we can see sort of what is the linearity, what is the sort of effect size of the topic itself on the amount of engagement.

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:44.280
So I think there's loads of things that you can do. I mean, we have everybody's email address, right? Because we emailed everybody to join this hangout. What are the domains of people that are joining the hangout?

00:33:45.280 --> 00:34:04.280
Yeah, I didn't mean to ask you a free consultancy type of question. But I'm just saying, I'm using as example, because we all are very familiar with the hangout, of course. But yeah, thank you. I see Alan asked a question in the chat a little bit earlier. Alan, want to jump in?

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:31.280
Yeah, hi, Peter. I'm curious, coming from prior roles and experience into working with LA County, if there were things that directly carried over, or if there were, like, assumptions you ran into that broke there, like, does success look different when you're working with an agency like that versus in other places? And what carried over cleanly? What assumptions broke? Just, you know, how that experience differed from what you've been doing previously?

00:34:31.280 --> 00:35:00.280
So I would say working with LA County, since it was more of a getting started consultancy, we have a framework for getting started. And we like to think of it as sort of the same way that you would have a boot camp, which is like just getting a lay of the landscape, getting visibility on the language, and getting to deliver something to them as an example that they want to answer within the same session, for example.

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:03.280
Or the same group of sessions.

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:17.280
And I think what I'm doing in companies is different, which is, it's not so much about, I don't spend a lot of time talking about methodologies, or how I get to a conclusion.

00:35:17.280 --> 00:35:31.280
I spend a lot more time talking about the nexus, the connection between the data science product itself, and the recommendations I'm making. So I spend more time on the inferencing part.

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:47.280
And I spend with, you know, and commercial work with somebody like LA County, I spend more time on how do we get there. And data visualization, I would say, is probably the most powerful part of that.

00:35:48.280 --> 00:36:03.280
For organizations like county governments that aren't going to have big expensive paid tools, like they're not going to have Looker or something like that, when there's many, many thousands of people that would need a seat for that product, right?

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:23.280
And not everybody there, like you have in a technology company, not everybody there is going to write SQL. And so Looker becomes sort of not useful, because if you want to build those views, under those views are big queries that are essentially aggregating data together for a specific visualization purpose.

00:36:24.280 --> 00:36:41.280
So I think that it is making sure that you're answering a question that they're interested in, getting them started inside of the IDE, and then being able to leverage what are the most valuable parts of the programming language for a new user.

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:45.280
Thanks, I appreciate hearing that.

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:57.280
I see, I think Jared had a question earlier, I'll read it, but it's do you use a customer data platform? And maybe if you could tell us what that means as well.

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:06.280
I'm sorry, you're asking the person asking the question.

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:15.280
I'm asking for Jared, because I saw a little star next to it. But do you use a customer data platform, a CDP?

00:37:16.280 --> 00:37:19.280
Yeah, absolutely. So most marketing works are going to use a CDP.

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:22.280
Can you let us know just what that is?

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:30.280
Yeah, it's essentially a way of connecting users to marketing, for the most simple explanation.

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:54.280
For example, I think at Toast, like many places, when you engage in a piece of marketing content, based upon the ability to track, say it's a piece of content or an ad, something else, a website that you might visit that belongs to that domain, you'll be put into a campaign.

00:37:55.280 --> 00:38:00.280
And the campaign is specific to that engagement that you've had in there and their marketing.

00:38:01.280 --> 00:38:06.280
And the goal of that is essentially to move somebody through a marketing model.

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:18.280
If you're selling a product that's expensive, like if you're selling an enterprise level SaaS product, that's going to be very different than somebody who's selling a product on Instagram, right?

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:31.280
Because those are very transactional immediately, right? You see that ad for this or that clothing item or something, and that starts to move the transaction along right away, you probably complete the transaction within a day.

00:38:32.280 --> 00:38:48.280
And so when you're thinking about what marketing should accomplish, it should accomplish a few things in that funnel, which is creating awareness for your product, delivering content around how you're solving a problem for a customer more than anything else.

00:38:49.280 --> 00:39:01.280
And then telling your story about how other users are getting value from that product, and then eventually connecting you with someone who could tell you more about how this might work in your specific environment.

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:08.280
I think the best SaaS companies tell that story often, and they tell it in as many places as they can.

00:39:08.280 --> 00:39:22.280
If I think about the case of Toast, a lot of the growth that Toast has seen is inside of domains that were not part of their core customer base, but where their solution was relevant.

00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:27.280
And those are things like food trucks and bars and restaurants.

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:40.280
And by paying attention to the types of customers you're acquiring and what channels you're acquiring them in, what they're consuming inside of that funnel will give you signals on the types of work you can do inside of a CDP.

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:50.280
It's interesting. I was thinking back to COVID, when Toast was helping out a lot of restaurants who were suddenly doing a lot of takeout.

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:57.280
And one of those restaurants was my mom's bar in Connecticut, and just helping her get stuff done.

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:07.280
But I imagine there was some big analysis done after the fact to see what was the impact of that, giving away some of your services during COVID.

00:40:08.280 --> 00:40:14.280
Right. I think that one of the things that I think is really important to think about is,

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:20.280
whether you're an enterprise customer or you're an individual business owner.

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:22.280
Zoom is an example of that.

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:32.280
Right. I think that one of the things that, especially one of the things SaaS companies do is to get you started inside of the product.

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:41.280
Whether you're an enterprise customer or you're an individual business owner.

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:43.280
Zoom is an example of that.

00:40:44.280 --> 00:40:48.280
It wasn't that long ago, I worked at Citrix in 2016.

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:54.280
You know, GoToMeeting was an Oracle's product, but really sort of the only competitors we had.

00:40:55.280 --> 00:40:57.280
And now nobody knows who GoToMeeting is.

00:40:57.280 --> 00:41:04.280
In just a couple of short years, Zoom invested in a product and went after verticalists, right?

00:41:04.280 --> 00:41:08.280
They went after very specific verticals of who would be successful with their tool.

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:12.280
And they told that story really, really well.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:15.280
And now Zoom owns that market, essentially.

00:41:16.280 --> 00:41:19.280
So I think you're right. It's like getting someone inside the tool.

00:41:19.280 --> 00:41:22.280
And you can start measuring the contribution of that, right?

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:28.280
You can, for example, the way that we usually get inside of a tool is through a trial, through a free trial.

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:34.280
And you can start measuring the conversion rates out of that trial for different types of customers.

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:39.280
And maybe even different types of locations to understand how much value you're extracting.

00:41:40.280 --> 00:41:42.280
Alan, I see you just put a question in. Want to go next?

00:41:44.280 --> 00:41:51.280
Yeah, thanks. I think this is sort of exploring, like, what does a CDP do a little bit more?

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:55.280
Because I've been in this conversation a bunch, and people say, we've got to have a CDP.

00:41:55.280 --> 00:42:02.280
And they describe it, and it feels a lot like it's a CRM plus other stuff.

00:42:02.280 --> 00:42:05.280
And it feels like it's sort of this incantation that they say.

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:11.280
And it's hard to actually define, like, functionally, what's it additively doing?

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:19.280
So if you've got a – it turns into what feels like a sort of, like, well, this one goes to 11 sort of argument for me sometimes.

00:42:19.280 --> 00:42:23.280
And, like, I still don't understand exactly what you're telling me you need.

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:27.280
And I'm not in the seat to, like, drive getting that thing anymore.

00:42:27.280 --> 00:42:30.280
But I'm often, like, hanging along with these conversations.

00:42:30.280 --> 00:42:37.280
So, like, functionally, Peter, is there, like, a way that you can concisely differentiate those things?

00:42:37.280 --> 00:42:45.280
Or is it my perception right that, like, these are sort of in a big bucket together, and it's hard to differentiate?

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:53.280
I think that the best way of thinking, conceiving of a CDP is what you're trying to accomplish.

00:42:54.280 --> 00:43:00.280
I sort of kind of go back to what we talked about initially of how would you do an ROI analysis.

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:10.280
There – you first need to find what it is that you're trying to accomplish and who your customer is and what kind of marketing you're doing.

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:18.280
So, for example, if I'm a product marketer, a lot of what I'm going to be doing is non-transactional, right?

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:24.280
It's creating awareness. It's telling the story of my product.

00:43:24.280 --> 00:43:32.280
It might even be including, like, having events and things like that where you're talking about the product to respective customers.

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:44.280
But I would spend time, based on your type of marketing, looking at those different tools, looking to see what the tool most accomplishes what you're trying to accomplish.

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:59.280
So, yeah, so that makes sense. That makes CDP feel more like it is a process or an activity versus a platform, which is often what it's shaped as in the conversations that I'm in.

00:43:59.280 --> 00:44:01.280
Is that the right way to think of it?

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:11.280
It is an aggregation of activities and the right tools for the job versus a thing that you get to do all that stuff?

00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:16.280
So, okay, let's talk about a specific one. Let's make it very specific.

00:44:16.280 --> 00:44:19.280
So, I mean, Salesforce is a CDP.

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:20.280
Okay.

00:44:20.280 --> 00:44:21.280
Okay.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:28.280
Salesforce is going to aggregate, like you said, all of the events for every one of your contacts.

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:29.280
Yep.

00:44:29.280 --> 00:44:33.280
And a contact will just be an email, essentially just an email address.

00:44:33.280 --> 00:44:42.280
And that's going to be able to map to some customer journey, right, given a sufficient analytical resources.

00:44:42.280 --> 00:44:44.280
So, Salesforce is a CDP.

00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:47.280
I mean, but there are other CDPs that don't do the same thing.

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:51.280
So, for example, a Twilio is a CDP.

00:44:51.280 --> 00:45:01.280
Twilio is the anonymized technology that communicates between you and your driver at Lyft or Uber.

